## 3.2 Delivery path and forged headers

The message contains four `Received:` headers. **They are not equally trustworthy.**

`Received:` headers are prepended by each handling server, so the chain reads bottom-up. Any header added before the message reached infrastructure under trusted control is attacker-supplied and may be fabricated. In this message the first trusted hop is `mx.google.com`.

### Trusted portion

```
Received: from unbeatablecloud.us.com (unbeatablecloud.us.com. [51.161.21.203])
        by mx.google.com with ESMTPS id af79cd13be357-...
        (version=TLS1_3 cipher=TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384 bits=256/256);
        Thu, 09 Jul 2026 02:52:44 -0700 (PDT)
```

Added by Google on receipt. This is the only hop corroborated by an independent party, and it establishes a **direct submission from `51.161.21.203` to Google's MX**, a single hop with no intermediate relay.

### Fabricated portion

```
Received: from njmta-53.sailthru.com (173.228.155.53) by dailybeast-a.sailthru.com
        id h1t86m1qqbs3 ... (envelope-from delivery@mx.sailthru.com)
Received: from nj1-madbrick.flt (172.18.20.7) by njmta-53.sailthru.com
        id h1t7vc1qqbsf ... (envelope-from delivery@mx.sailthru.com)
```

These assert that the message transited Sailthru, a legitimate email service provider, including an instance apparently associated with a well-known publisher. **The assertion is false.** Grounds:

1. **Position in the chain.** Both sit below the Google hop, placing them within the attacker-controlled portion of the message.
2. **Contradiction with the trusted hop.** Google recorded direct receipt from `51.161.21.203`. Had the message genuinely originated at Sailthru, Google would have received it from Sailthru infrastructure.
3. **Non-routable address.** `172.18.20.7` is RFC 1918 private address space and cannot appear as a legitimate public relay hop.
4. **Envelope inconsistency.** These headers cite `delivery@mx.sailthru.com` as envelope-from, whereas the actual authenticated envelope sender was `Return@…waterints[.]com`.

**Purpose.** Fabricated headers referencing a reputable ESP are intended to influence reputation-based filtering, and to mislead any recipient or analyst who reads the chain without first establishing which hops are trustworthy.

> **Method note.** No conclusion in this report relies on the fabricated headers. The delivery path is established solely from the hop recorded by Google.

