## 3.3 Structural evasion

Several characteristics indicate deliberate filter evasion rather than incidental sloppiness.

### Unicode homoglyphs in the display name

```
From: "𝗣aym𝗲nt_Declin𝗲d©" <edupreutnxjoip.77475570789982@5ibhni.nx8om7.dskpn2[.]us>
```

| Character | Codepoint | Block |
|---|---|---|
| `𝗣` | U+1D5E3 | Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols |
| `𝗲` | U+1D5F2 | Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols |

The display name is not ASCII. It renders visually as "Payment_Declined" but does not match that string at byte level, defeating exact-match rules on sender display names. The trailing `©` serves the same purpose.

**Detection implication:** display-name rules must operate on Unicode-normalised text, or they can be bypassed at no cost to the attacker.

### Message disguised as a delivery status notification

```
Content-Type: multipart/report; report-type=delivery-status
```

The message declares itself a delivery status notification, meaning an automated bounce. The actual content is an HTML credential-harvesting page. Delivery status notifications are frequently subject to lighter filtering as system-generated mail, making the mismatch a plausible deliberate choice.

### Absent Message-ID

```
Message-ID: <7did4m1y.1g9q0220.9hj1wc.022ySMTPIN_ADDED_MISSING@mx.google.com>
```

The `SMTPIN_ADDED_MISSING` marker indicates the message **arrived with no `Message-ID` header** and one was generated by Google on receipt. Legitimate mail systems reliably set this header. Its absence indicates crude sending tooling rather than a standards-compliant MTA.

### Bayesian poisoning in the plaintext part

The `text/plain` alternative contains no meaningful content: an unrelated header line, a long numeric string, and approximately 180 characters of random lowercase consonants. Recipients using an HTML-capable client never see it.

Its function is to dilute the statistical profile of the message against Bayesian spam classifiers. Its presence is itself a strong indicator of automated bulk mailing.

